---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const title = 'About';
const description =
  'About Anivar A. Aravind — engineering leader, systems thinker, and independent researcher. Two decades in the hard seat across regulated FinTech, B2B2C global commerce, and population-scale public computing.';
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} ogType="profile">
  <article>
    <header>
      <span class="kicker">About</span>
      <h1>About Anivar.</h1>
    </header>

    <p class="lede">
      I work where engineering has to ship commercially, hold up under board
      scrutiny, and reach population scale at once. Two decades in that seat —
      regulated FinTech, global commerce across six markets, multilingual
      public computing used by hundreds of millions. Alongside the day job, I
      run a continuing line of independent work on infrastructure that can be
      inspected, reproduced, and corrected.
    </p>

    <h2>Principles</h2>

    <h3>1. The hard seat.</h3>
    <p>
      Operating where commercial pressure, board exposure, and public consequence
      all hold at once is the only seat that produces the judgment a board
      actually needs. Theory describes the system; the hard seat is where the
      system meets contradiction — a regulator and a customer asking for
      opposite things on the same week, audit-grade controls landing under a
      revenue deadline, the third 3DS edge case the spec did not anticipate.
      That seat is where adversarial systems judgment is forged. It cannot be
      franchised from the outside.
    </p>

    <h3>2. Adversarial systems judgment.</h3>
    <p>
      The instinct is to find the failure mode before it finds the system.
      Every architecture proposal carries an unspoken bet about what stays
      stable and what does not — provider, regulation, attacker capability,
      latency budget, supply chain, the team. Finding which of those bets is
      the load-bearing one and what happens when it breaks is the engineering
      content that matters in the boardroom. It cannot be franchised, only
      practised — and only practised in the seat.
    </p>

    <h3>3. An independent line of work.</h3>
    <p>
      I write Layer&nbsp;8, publish working papers under CC0, and ship
      projects (OpenSLM, Corrigibility, Indic Project) outside any employer
      because the discipline keeps the day job honest. The day job runs on
      shipped product and shareholder interest; the independent line runs on
      whether the argument holds when nothing depends on it. The two
      registers correct each other. Without the independent line, technical
      conviction collapses into whatever the current quarter rewards. Without
      the day job, the independent line collapses into commentary.
    </p>

    <h2>Selected recognition</h2>
    <ul class="t-list">
      <li>
        <div class="t-list__row">
          <span class="t-list__label">2024</span>
          <p class="t-list__body"><em>Deccan Herald</em> Changemaker, recognising sustained work on accountable digital infrastructure.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <div class="t-list__row">
          <span class="t-list__label">2024 / 2025</span>
          <p class="t-list__body">Just AI Awards — jury.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <div class="t-list__row">
          <span class="t-list__label">Standing</span>
          <p class="t-list__body">SFLC.in advisory board.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <div class="t-list__row">
          <span class="t-list__label">Standards</span>
          <p class="t-list__body">Contributor, BIS&nbsp;IS&nbsp;16333 (Part&nbsp;3) — India's national standard for Indic-language computing. Upstream contributions at Unicode, IDNA, ICANN; ECMAScript&nbsp;2025 work on Mozilla Rhino.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Contact</h2>
    <p>
      For media: <a href="/press/">/press/</a> &middot;
      For citations: <a href="/research/">/research/</a> &middot;
      Direct: <a href="mailto:ping@anivar.net">ping@anivar.net</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
